Improves your body’s ability to burn fat faster and more effectively

Body Archives “switches on” specific fat-burning hormones that tell your body to break down and burn stored fat. By activating hormones known to have a direct effect on fat burning, PhenGold can help you burn off even the most stubborn fat for good.

”Within four weeks I dropped 9 pounds and lost 2 inches around my waist”

Kate, US
Caffeine, L-tyrosine, rhodiola, green tea and the capsaicin in cayenne pepper all help your body burn fat faster by increasing levels of fat-burning hormones HSL (hormone-sensitive lipase), epinephrine, norepinephrine and adiponectin1.
Green tea, green coffee, caffeine and L-theanine can help shrink fat cells by significantly reducing triglycerides2, a type of fat stored inside your fat cells and the main form of fat in your body.
Capsaicin in cayenne pepper may help reduce stubborn belly fat by boosting levels of a fat-burning enzyme called HSL (hormone-sensitive lipase) specifically in your abdominal area3.

The faster your metabolism, the faster your body burns fat. Body Archives stimulates your body’s natural metabolic rate and speeds up the rate at which calories and stored fat are converted into energy. Which means you’ll naturally burn more calories and more unwanted fat every day. Even while you’re doing nothing.

”Seeing the weight dropping off gave me the boost I needed to keep going”

Dave, US
Caffeine has been found in studies to increase metabolism by up to 11% and boost fat burning by as much as 29%4.
Capsaicinoids in cayenne pepper could help you burn as many as 50 extra calories per day5. Studies have also found that green tea extract could help you burn up to 17% more fat, especially if taken before exercise6.
B vitamins provide essential metabolism support7 by helping convert carbohydrates, fats and proteins into energy instead of letting them turn to fat. Vitamin B6 also helps increase production of L-carnitine, an amino acid that helps your body burn fat.
Caffeine, green coffee, green tea and capsaicin increase levels of adiponectin, a fat-burning hormone which boosts your metabolism and improves your body's ability to use carbohydrates for energy instead of fat-storage8.

Curbs cravings and hunger to help you stop snacking and stay in control of your eating

By acting as a natural appetite suppressant, PhenGold can help you feel fuller and help reduce food cravings in between meals. Making it easier for you to avoid overeating, reduce your calorie intake and stay on track with your healthy diet.

”I struggled with eating fewer calories which inevitably led to snacking. That’s where Body Archives made the biggest difference”

Jane, US
Capsaicin and caffeine are natural hunger suppressants. Studies have found that they can help reduce cravings and hunger, decrease your appetite and help you feel more full when you eat9.
B vitamins could help curb carb and sugar cravings by helping your body use carbohydrates more effectively. Which means you won’t feel the need to eat more than you need.
B vitamins can help prevent stress-related food cravings because they play a vital role in helping your body manage stress - a key cause of cravings and increased appetite10.
As natural mood boosters, L-theanine, L-tyrosine, B vitamins and DMAE may help you gain control over emotional eating by reducing the feelings of stress, anxiety and depression that can trigger the impulse to turn to food for comfort11.

Does Body Archives have any side effects?

Body Archives is completely safe. That’s because we use only 100% natural ingredients that have been thoroughly researched, tested and proven to be safe and effective.

Body Archives does contain 225mg of caffeine, 500mg of green tea and 100mg of green coffee per daily dose. So if you’re sensitive to caffeine or if you do experience any adverse effects from these stimulants, we recommend you limit or avoid your use of any other caffeinated products while you’re taking Body Archives .

A small number of customers have reported feelings of dizziness, shakiness and/or headaches when using Body Archives . We have found that ensuring Body Archives is taken before food as directed and decreasing or avoiding use of other caffeinated products while using Body Archives resolves these symptoms.

Body Archives is not recommended if you are pregnant or breastfeeding. If you have any existing health issues or you are currently taking any medication, you should consult your healthcare professional before taking Body Archives to ensure it is suitable for you. Otherwise, Body Archives is safe for healthy adults when used as directed.
Is Body Archives FDA approved?

Body Archives is manufactured in FDA registered, Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP) certified facilities in the USA. This means that Body Archives is produced and controlled to international quality standards throughout every step of the manufacturing process. So you can be sure that when you order Body Archives , you are getting a safe supplement of the highest quality.

Clinical References
1. Caffeine, L-tyrosine, rhodiola, green tea and capsaicin increase HSL (hormone-sensitive lipase), epinephrine, norepinephrine and adiponectin.
  • Capsaicin significantly up-regulated levels of genes involved in lipid catabolism such as hormone sensitive lipase (HSL):
    Lee MS, Kim CT, Kim IH, Kim Y. Effects of capsaicin on lipid catabolism in 3T3-L1 adipocytes. Phytother Res. 2011 Jun;25(6):935-9. doi: 10.1002/ptr.3339. Epub 2010 Nov 17. PMID: 21626599
  • Capsaicin treatment boosted visceral adipose expression of hormone-sensitive lipase:
    Kang JH, Kim CS, Han IS, et al. Capsaicin, a spicy component of hot peppers, modulates adipokine gene expression and protein release from obese-mouse adipose tissues and isolated adipocytes, and suppresses the inflammatory responses of adipose tissue macrophages. FEBS Lett 2007;581:4389–96. doi:10.1016/j.febslet.2007.07.082
  • Topical application of capsaicin increased expression of adiponectin, significantly reduced visceral fat and markedly reduced the size of fat cells in mice:
    Lee GR, Shin MK, Yoon DJ, Kim AR, Yu R, Park NH, Han IS. Topical application of capsaicin reduces visceral adipose fat by affecting adipokine levels in high-fat diet-induced obese mice. Obesity (Silver Spring). 2013 Jan;21(1):115-22. doi: 10.1002/oby.20246. PMID: 23505175
  • Tyrosine is the precursor of epinephrine:
    National Library of Medicine, Compound Summary: Tyrosine 


  • Rhodiola rosea stimulates norepinephrine activity:
    American Botanical Council, Issue: 56, Page: 40-52,  Rhodiola rosea: A Phytomedicinal Overview 
  • Caffeine Increases blood levels of epinephrine and norepinephrine: 
    Keijzers GB, De Galan BE, Tack CJ, Smits P. Caffeine can decrease insulin sensitivity in humans. Diabetes Care. 2002 Feb;25(2):364-9. doi: 10.2337/diacare.25.2.364. PMID: 11815511
  • Capsaicin stimulates the release of adrenaline (epinephrine):
    Tremblay A, Arguin H, Panahi S. Capsaicinoids: a spicy solution to the management of obesity? Int J Obes (Lond). 2016 Aug;40(8):1198-204. doi: 10.1038/ijo.2015.253. Epub 2015 Dec 21. PMID: 26686003

     

  • Green tea increases thermogenesis and inhibits an enzyme that degrades norepinephrine:
    Shixian Q, VanCrey B, Shi J, Kakuda Y, Jiang Y. Green tea extract thermogenesis-induced weight loss by epigallocatechin gallate inhibition of catechol-O-methyltransferase. J Med Food. 2006 Winter;9(4):451-8. doi: 10.1089/jmf.2006.9.451. PMID: 17201629
  • A review of studies suggests a positive association between coffee and adiponectin level and the positive role of green tea in adiponectin concentration:
    Izadi V, Larijani B, Azadbakht L. Is Coffee and Green Tea Consumption Related to Serum Levels of Adiponectin and Leptin? Int J Prev Med. 2018 Dec 5;9:106. doi: 10.4103/ijpvm.IJPVM_37_14. PMID: 30622689
2. Green tea, green coffee, caffeine and L-theanine significantly reduce triglycerides.
  • Both in vitro and animal experiments have shown that green tea catechins can significantly reduce levels of plasma triglycerides:  
    Xu, R., Yang, K., Li, S. et al. Effect of green tea consumption on blood lipids: a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. Nutr J 19, 48 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12937-020-00557-5 
  • Theanine and green tea catechins significantly reduced triglyceride levels in the serum and livers of laboratory mice:
    Zheng G, Sayama K, Okubo T, Juneja LR, Oguni I. Anti-obesity effects of three major components of green tea, catechins, caffeine and theanine, in mice. In Vivo. 2004 Jan-Feb;18(1):55-62. PMID: 15011752

  • Both in vitro and animal experiments have shown that green tea catechins can significantly reduce levels of plasma triglycerides:  
    Xu, R., Yang, K., Li, S. et al. Effect of green tea consumption on blood lipids: a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. Nutr J 19, 48 (2020). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12937-020-00557-5 
  • Theanine and green tea catechins significantly reduced triglyceride levels in the serum and livers of laboratory mice:
    Zheng G, Sayama K, Okubo T, Juneja LR, Oguni I. Anti-obesity effects of three major components of green tea, catechins, caffeine and theanine, in mice. In Vivo. 2004 Jan-Feb;18(1):55-62. PMID: 15011752
4. Caffeine can increase metabolism by up to 11% and fat burning by as much as 29%.
  • Caffeine ingestion increased energy expenditure 13% and doubled the turnover of lipids in healthy young men:
    Acheson KJ, Gremaud G, Meirim I, Montigon F, Krebs Y, Fay LB, Gay LJ, Schneiter P, Schindler C, Tappy L. Metabolic effects of caffeine in humans: lipid oxidation or futile cycling? Am J Clin Nutr. 2004 Jan;79(1):40-6. doi: 10.1093/ajcn/79.1.40. PMID: 14684395 
  • 100mg caffeine increased the resting metabolic rate of both lean and postobese human volunteers by 3-4%:
    Dulloo, A., Geissler, A.C., Horton, T., Collins, A. & Miller, D.S. (1989): ‘Normal caffeine consumption: influence on thermogenesis and daily energy expenditure in lean and postobese human volunteers’. American Journal of Clinical Nutrition, 1989 Jan;49(1):44-50. PMID 2912010

 

 

  • Caffeine-induced thermogenesis increased metabolic rate by 4% in healthy male volunteers:
